Monday, January 1, 1934

Still too sick to work. Made a few labels and punched last specimens.
Read Anthony Adverse and listened to Stanford-Columbia game.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 06/25/2014 03:22 PM
  • jmorris 01/26/2012 04:09 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Tuesday, January 2, 1934

Talked to the SD herp. society tonight; about 30 present; snakes of S.D. County.

Records from Berry Campbell's Arizona paper.

Pena Blanca Spring
Scaphiopus hammondii
Bufo alvarius
Bufo punctatus
Hyla arenicolor
Gastrophryne texensis
Rana pipiens
Rana tarahumarae
Hypsiglena ochrorhynchus
Thamnophis eques
Trimorphodon lyrophanes
Kinsternon sonoriense

Miller Canyon, Huachucas
Bufo debilis
Rana pipiens
Thamnophis eques
Oxybelis microphthalmus
Cistalus lepidus

Walker Canyon
Hyla arenicolor

Patagoinia
Primirphodon cyrophanes
Hyla arenicolor

Wednesday, January 3, 1934

In a letter from Harold Woodall oreganus and scutulatus from a ranch 20 mi. N. of Mohave. Trimorphodon from Silverado Canyon, Orange Co., 31 dorsal, 41 caudal blotches. Anal entire. Worked on the annual list tonight.

Patagonia (continued) G. texensis

1/2 mi. NW Miller Peak, Huachucas
Hyla exinia

Sonoita
Rhinocheilus lecontei

Nogales
Terrapene ornata

Thursday, January 4, 1934

Drove out to Rose Canyon and back - a clear warm day. First time over the new Atlantic Street Boulevard. 16 miles. Nothing seen.

Cook worked this morning. Still too sick to take much interest in the proceedings.

Page Edit History:
  • jgoldenberg 08/24/2012 04:32 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Friday, January 5, 1934

Cook worked part of the day, and finished practically everything in sight.

Out to dinner tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • jgoldenberg 08/24/2012 04:33 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Saturday, January 6, 1934

Cook came back today and worked in the morning clearing up odds and ends.

Worked by fits and starts all day; too sick to do anything but more or less mechanical work.

Sunday, January 7, 1934

Worked on and off all day when not feeling too rotten; brought the 1933 tabulations up to date finishing the table for the year.

Page Edit History:

Monday, January 8, 1934

Recd today from the NH Museum a worm snake from Mission Valley.

Recd from Grand Canyon Museum 2 rattlers for examination.

Gall bladder photos today

Friday, January 12, 1934

Felt like working tonight for the first time in weeks and did some work in the rattle.

Last X-rays today.

Union called up tonight and said there was an AP dispatch on the wire to the effect that Jackley in Pierre had sent me 750 rattlers.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/21/2012 05:53 PM

Saturday, January 13, 1934

Pretty sick today but nevertheless made some progress on the rattler problem. The rattle write-up is now finished in all major particulars. Some work remains to be done on the figures - also the conclusions.

Went to Natural History annual meeting at noon.

Recd from Perkins a worm snake from Mission Valley.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 06/25/2014 03:26 PM
  • lwilliams 08/27/2012 05:32 PM
  • jgoldenberg 08/24/2012 04:42 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Sunday, January 14, 1934

Felt somewhat better today, at least up to evening and got quite a bit of work done. Pickled 5 snakes. Studied a lot of rattlers - rattle matrices - to make sure of the method of slipping back.

Movie tonight.

Born at the zoo today a brood of lucasensis

1 alive
3 well formed but dead
1 badly formed
6 infertile eggs

Sunday, January 28, 1934

Worked on rate case all day.

Paul DR Ruthling called late in the afternoon; talked reptiles, and Mexico and had a very interesting visit. He told me of catching C. polystictus in the tules of Lake Chapala in June. They were very plentiful far out in the lake. Took refuge in the water when hunted.

Page Edit History:
  • erintmas 01/08/2013 04:16 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Getting ready for rate case; too tired for work tonight.

Tuesday, January 30, 1934

Rate case all day.

Ruthling called tonight. Talked Mexico. The polystictus were collected Aug. 21 1919. About 20 to 25 were seen.

Friday, February 2, 1934

Very sick this AM and in fact all night. Had to get the doc at 4AM. Two docs at 10AM and me again in the afternoon. Better in the evening but all in.

Missed v. pills today.

Spasm again tonight - bad night - Had Dr. Redlings.

No arsenic pill tonight.

Thursday, March 8, 1934

Returned from Los Angeles this afternoon, starting at 1:30. A warm day.
1 small gopher DOR at San Clemente. Grass saved specimen.
1 Pacific rattler large DOR at Rose Canyon. Grass.
53 miles in the county.

Stopped for a few moments at Laguna and saw Perkins-Artran was not home.

Gave me a batrachoseps from Laguna. Also had a ring-neck from the same place.

Told me they had collected ruber and mitchellii lately within a few miles of Capistrano Hot Springs. Exact locality later.

Cook worked all day today.

Notes:

erintmas

Pretty sure I spelled scientific name right on 12th line, but not a 100%.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 06/25/2014 03:37 PM

  • erintmas 01/14/2013 11:57 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Friday, March 9, 1934

This morning at 10:30 started on an inspection trip with Claude Brown. It was very hot in the back country and uncomfortably warm at the coast. Went via Broadway Extension, Spring Valley, north via Grossmont, El Cajon, Santee, Foster, Ramona, San Pasqual, Escondido, Oceanside via Vista, San Luis Rey, Bonsall Bridge, returned to Oceanside on north side of river. Here Brown caught the train. Returned to S.D. via coast highway, arriving at 4:30. 135 miles.

1 Garter DOR med grass Chollas Hts.
1 Gopher DOR small grass Riverview. Saved.
2 Pac. garters L DOR do grass-river.
1 Garter M DOR do brush.
1 Red racer. Lost on L Ronnseer brush. Was crossing the road. Raised his head and stopped to look at us from the edge. Was grayish with a black head. Cross bars in evidence.

Saw quite a few lizards and 1 dead horned toad. Cook worked all day.

Notes:

erintmas

A couple things I'm not sure about on this page: (1) is it 2 Pac. Garters or maybe another number, also is it "do grass-river" for location, (2) for 1 Garter M DOR is it "do brush", (3) for 1 Red racer think its say "lost on L" then a weird word (not sure if I spelled it right).

Dr. Mosauer called on the phone.

Sunday, March 11, 1934

Worked all day on miscellaneous records. Pickled a few specimens. There is certainly no time for research and writing when the spring material has begun to come in.

Out to function tonight.

Monday, March 12, 1934

Saturday, March 17, 1934

2 Gophers L DOR grass Morena

Company in the evening - Kuhns.

Sunday, March 18, 1934

Still working on head-length. Pickled a few specimens in the afternoon.

Discovered this afternoon that mitchellii from the Cape is clearly a valid subspecies based on head size. Always thought this looked queer but never appreciated the extent of the difference until I examined the Cape material brought in by Lewis last summer.

Wednesday, May 2, 1934

Rate case. Worked tonight.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(May 23d Continued from May 15th)
at all. Gave her permanganate toward the last.

Called on Harold Woodall at Long Beach. Checked his Trimorphodon from Silverado Canyon, Orange Co. It seems to have the usual San Diego coloration; dark brown with split blotches. 31 body spots, 14 tail. Anal entire. This was found in December; saw it in a crack. Another from Black Star Canyon was DOR and not saved.

Woodall told me that a man named Kirby at Johnson's Long Beach snake show was bitten by a big red rattler (ferrale). This had been milked shortly before but they didn't get much. Evidently it was badly done. He was bitten in front of the shoulder so there was no chance to use a tourniquet. Held on and chewed. Both fangs entered. There were very extensive swelling and hemorrhage. Antivenin was not used. Suction was tried immediately. The crisis was passed 72 hrs. Still not completely recovered after some weeks.

Notes:

erintmas

Not sure if I spelled the word in third paragraph in the parentheses right.

Thursday, May 10, 1934

Out tonight.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(May 19th Continued)
noticeable amongst all the rest of the snakes. The moleraus and tigris were said to have been taken 40 mi. NE of Phoenix, but he was not certain enough of this to take it as trustworthy. He had 2 or 3 large Texas atrox, noticeably darker than the Arizona specimens. Had a long nose, one very large bull snake (looked to be over 6 ft) and a number of Boyle's Kings said to have been taken in the vicinity of Phoenix. They are as large as any of our local snakes and have narrow light rings.

Evans says this is a poor year for both snakes and gila monsters; not many people are bringing them in. It is now too late to expect much. He gets all of his best specimens in early spring.

Stopped at Cactus Garden 8 mi. SE of Wickenburg but they had only 2 small atrox.

Started west from Wickenburg at 4:30. The country along the Hassayampa S. of Wickenburg looks good. Also the country immediately to the west.

(Continued on May 10th)

Monday, May 14, 1934

A letter from Earl Saunders reports Rhinocheilus lecontei 12 mi E. of Mesa, Ariz = Desert Wells.
-----------------------------------------------------------
(May 23d Continued)
characteristic of the coastal snakes.

A California King from Laguna Beach has the vertebral stripe fairly regular, but the sides are mottled, spotted and criss-cross high up like a hybrid.

Artran states ring-necks will eat young of the same kind.

There were a number of Mitches from the Elsinore Mountains (San Juan Canyon) near the Orange-Riverside Co line. This was an unusually fine lot. Some were quite large; about as large as any I have seen from San Diego Co. They were also quite uniform in color; a beautiful burnt orange - different from anything previously seen. They were not exactly uniform, but the largest especially were this color. The young ones were less specialized.

Rubers from San Juan and Trabuco Canyons seemed normal; one was a little light, like desert specimens.

There were a number of Boyle's Kings.

(Continued on May 15)

  • erintmas 01/23/2013 10:00 PM

Tuesday, May 15, 1934

Rate case today.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(May 23d Continued from May 14th)
from the vicinity of Laguna and these all had noticeably narrow light rings; yellow not white and as thin as eastern Kings. A single specimen from Coachella was in strong contrast, with wide white stripes.

There was also a series of oreganus from Marysville Buttes all quite uniform in color and pattern. All have white faces and white patches at the angle of the mouth. The green anterior color changes to sharply contrasting black and gray rings at the tail, and the last quarter of the body.

I traded a boa for a small rattler from Fair Oaks, 20 miles east of Sacramento and one of the mitches. The one previously notes from Grass Valley is not the town of Grass Valley, but a valley by this name east of Sacramento.

Artran told me of a fatal case of rattler bite at Newman this year. A 15 year old girl. Was given 3 doses of antivenin but died in 14 hours. The doctors didn't seem to know how to handle the case
(Continued on May 2)

Saturday, May 19, 1934

Started from Yuma this morning at 7:45 P.T. Moderately warm.

Got a C. c. baileyi in the Mohawk Mts (Mark 1)

Dup seen at Aztec.

Hunted for a short time in scattered black lava at sentinel (2 mi. W). Caught 2 chucks here and saw several more. Got a C. c. baileyi. And saw cally.

Found a large Dup DOR 6 mi. S. of Gillespie Dam. Saved.

Collared lizard and whip seen at Gillespie Dam.

Small Boyle's King DOR at Arlington (this on a detour) Fields. Perfectly black and white. Tail is ringed. Head has more black than usual run of S.D. Coppers. The stripes are even; the light are clear.

Nothing between here and Phoenix. Certainly a poor morning. Very few lizards were seen. Stopped at Hale's but could not see snakes as they were being fed. Got to Phoenix at 2 P.M.

Called on C L Evans at his Cactus Garden. He had about 20 rattlers mostly atrox. There may have been one or two scutes amongst these. Had 2 molossus and 1 large tigris usual small head very

1 Boyle's King L DOR Morena grass

Stopped at Artran and Perkins Serpentarium at Laguna Beach, seeing it for the first time. A clean neat exhibit with a number of interesting items as follows:
Patchnose from Laguna Canyon, 1 mile up. Usual coast phase. Another from Pinon Flat was about halfway between a coast and desert specimen.

A red racer from Laguna had the usual red color and dark head

Friday, May 25, 1934

Arrived in Los Angeles on the Lark this morning. Got the car and drove over to Lee Weinberger. He had a number of Louisiana snakes - not much else of interest. Had a fine collection of Oreganus said to be from the Ridge Route. Some were dark, others light like those from the San Joaquin Valley. Gave me 2.

Also saw Hautenbrinks material. He had a nice lot of sidewinders and atrox from Walken. Also a large tan mitch said to have been taken in Indio last August. Counted the spots on his Phyllorhynchus from Travertine Rock and found them to measure 42. He did not have the Trimorphodon; it had been loaned to Bogert.

1 Red Racer L DOR Capistrano fields (dark head).

1 Boyles King L DOR La Costa grass

53 miles in S.D. Country. Reached home at 2:30.

erintmas

Noted today a Sonora episcopa from Andrade without a vertebral stripe. Was unicolor; with the faint ghost of a spot on the neck.

Sunday, June 10, 1934

Spent the day on tigris and stephensi summaries and made good headway.

Finished counting the South Dakota juveniles. There now remain only about 50 adults to count and the entire South Dakota series will be complete.

Went to dinner at the McKay's tonight. Took Mac 10 g. of lucasensis venom for his experimental work. Saw some tame hylas and watched them croak from a short distance. Saw one dead snake in the road going out but had no time to stop.

Page Edit History:
  • erintmas 02/20/2013 08:10 PM

Monday, June 11, 1934

Lewis got in this morning. He had the following:
74 lucasensis
20 mitchellii
6 Enyo
6 Racers from Modae Maria Isle
1 Tree Snake
1 Dromicus from Seymour Isl
5 Boas
1 small racer from the Capi.

There were said have been 101 rattlers but I counted only 100. Lewis said it was very cold both at the Cape and at Cedros. At the latter place he did not stop. He stayed 2 weeks at the Cape (or made a trip up the gulf) while the rattlers were being collected. He said they had to be dug out. One man was badly bitten. 20 rattlers are to be sent to March. He evidently had word sent around that he didn't want racers or any other snakes but rattlers. He said one racer swam to the boat meaning I presume that it escaped from one of the boats bringing out rattlers for sale. One Guayaquil snake died enroute.

Notes:

Tuesday, June 12, 1934

Yesterday I started Mrs. Elizabeth Leslie of the SERA on tabulating work.

Received today a lot of lizards from Spain.

Went over the Lewis rattlers today and took 5 small lucasensis and one very thin adult which was in bad shape. This one died before I got it home. Many seem to be unusually thin as if in captivity for some time.

Recd yesterday from Cannon 2 yearling oreganus from Fletcher Hills.

Saturday, June 16, 1934

Went over to the zoo this morning and talked to Cy. Jr. He said the weather was rather unfavorable on both Clarion and Socorro. The saw 10 snakes on Clarion and got 9. They were mostly in the ice plant bordering the beach. The lizards were not over plentiful maybe on account of the weather. The brush is very dense on Socorro which makes hunting (except on the lava ridges) very difficult. Lizards seemed most plentiful on West San Benito.

Cook worked all day.

Saturday, June 30, 1934

Spent considerable time at the zoo and natural history museum this morning getting various matters straightened out.

Cook started to work again today.

Elmer Wood reported he found at 6:20 P.M. in Mahogany Canyon a Calif. King snake 34" long half swallowed by a Boyles King 40" long. The California King was about dead.

Cook and Philip worked nearly all day and made considerable headway with the Platteville counts.

I spent the afternoon on the labial correlation. Milked the rattlers in the evening.

Thus far of the last Lewis shipment I have had 26 lucasensis 1 enyo and 5 mitch. 1 lucasensis has been lost (spoiled).

Noted a 350 mm DOR Tantilla from Mission Valley, brot. in by Elmer Wood.

Friday, July 6, 1934

Cook and Philip worked all day. As of this date every rattler in the collection has been counted; for the first time in three years this is true, as it was not originally intended to count the Platteville fall 1931 series.

A small spotted night snake ate 2 small X. henshauri in captivity.

Color notes on two racers alive.M. lineatus from Maria Madre Island. Medium brown above. Each scale is edged with black, with a black spot at each end thus making a net. The head is uniform brown. The light lines on the sides are only slightly evident. Straw below; no pink. These colors should not change in captivity. M. anthonyi. Russet above. Pink and gray below anteriorly; clear pink posteriorly. The russet effect above is really mixed pink and gray. A net work of light scale edges on the sides gives the effect of light horizontal lines. The pink color which is very evident will change to brown in pickle. The head is russet. These two specs. photographed.

Friday, July 13, 1934

Rate case all day.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(July 14th, Cont)

of blood. They reached the next house got help and were taken to Jacumba, the ranch being in McCain Valley. He thought the pain was worst about 4 hrs after he was bitten. He was given one tube of antivenin at Jacumba and two more tubes somewhat later as it was brought out from San Diego by deputy sheriffs leaving at 10:15. The subsequent treatment is not known. He was still quite sick last night but is much better today. The pain is mostly in the leg; little above the knee. Some difficulty in breathing and pressure last night. Numbness on one side of the face yesterday and especially around the lips. Some swelling in the arm pit.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 06/25/2014 04:42 PM

Saturday, July 14, 1934

At the zoo this morning saw Prof. and Mrs. Wright of Cornell and talked with them on many subjects.

In the afternoon saw Pat Hutchinson 21 who was bitten by a rattler Thursday night at 7:30. He had gone out of his cabin to get a gun left leaning against a tree. Had removed his boots. He did not see the rattler which struck him as it was dark. He probably stepped on the snake but was not sure. It rattled after striking him but not before. Bit him in the ankle. The pain was intense immediately. He cut the wound and put in permanganate. Also tried a string tourniquet above the bite. Washed it out with distilled water. The woman did not suck the wound as she had a bad tooth. They started for help walking about 3 miles in the dark to the nearest house. They were out of gasoline for their own car. He fell many times. took a pint of whiskey enroute. Was in great pain and very weak but this may have been from loss

(Cont July 13)

Thursday, August 30, 1934

Went to Lakeview via highway; back by Mission Gorge. 30 miles. Nothing seen.

Cook was bitten by a Gila Monster Monday. He put it in a sack and then took hold of one corner to twist it and tie a knot in the mouth. The Gila bit instantly through the wall of the sack. Got his thumb and chewed. Felt the pain instantly. Put in a tourniquet and bled it. Had considerable pain, but little or no systemic effect. Hand continued to swell. Little swelling of the arm. Was given 10 cc of antivenin 48 hrs after the bite. The swelling then went down but impossible to say whether it would have done so without the antivenin.

Friday, August 31, 1934

Started for the desert this afternoon at 3:50. Went as far as the Kane Springs Junction. A hot, still dark night on the desert but no luck. Not a snake seen, alive or dead. Returned at 11:30. Total miles 204. Miles in San Diego County 182. Miles to be counted 104.

Saw a Coleonyx at 6:50 2 mi E. of the Narrows. It was then dusk. Got 2 others one just as we crossed the County Line, the other 5 miles east of the Line.

Talked to the boy at the Fallbrook CCC camp who killed a ruber supposed to be 6' long. He is 6' himself. Claims he held the end of the tail even with the top of his head, and the snake's head touched the ground.

Monday, September 10, 1934

Arrived in Chicago at 8:40 CST. Sunny and cool. Business at the office all morning. Left at 2:05 P.M. for Philadelphia.
-----------------------------------------------------------
(Sept 11 Continued)

was time later. Found much of great interest. The collection is larger and in better condition than I had expected based on previous reports; at least every specimen is tagged with a number. Of course the extent of the locality data available cannot be ascertained without the catalogues.

Fowler said the Gloyds had been there last week. Found Gloyd's notes on one or two specimens.

Called up Dunn in the evening but couldn't reach him; also Mom in N.Y. but she had left for Quebec.

Spent the evening writing letters and organizing for the work of the morrow.

A warm, sultry night; couldn't sleep well.

Tuesday, September 11, 1934

Arrived at Philadelphia at 9:58 EST. Not knowing 30th St was the only stop, nearly got carried on. In order not to lose any time went direct to the Academy, sending my baggage on to the hotel by taxi - a foolish thing to do, but it turned out all right. Found Fowler at the Academy and went right to work as they were expecting me. Stone was sick at home. Worked through the noon hour and up to 4:30 (the Academy closes a 5:00) . The accommodations are not very good but at least the basement was cool. And I was left entirely undisturbed. Unfortunately the accession ledge was at the binders so that nothing could be told about the specimens unless they happened to have locality tags attached which most of them lacked. The rattlers were all together at least such as have been accessioned. I started work by making a list of all rattlers (except Sistrurus) examining each specimen and got about half thought by quitting time. Set aside what was to counted if there

(Continued on Sept. 10)

Wednesday, September 12, 1934

Spent the day from 9 to 5 at the Philadelphia Academy, with no time off for lunch.

First talked with Fowler about the old days when Cope was alive and heard many interesting yarns. Fowler had acted as a go between, between Cope and the Academy following some disagreement. He knew Cope well and often saw him at work in his home.

Then to work. Carefully checked the two Phyllorhynchus including the type of decuratus; these were in good condition. Also checked two lichanura types. Then finished up the listing of the rattlers. After this counted as many as possible (17). The work was rather slow because of the condition of the snakes. Stone came in for a few moments today.

Sent aside a few specimens to be sent to me as a loan, which Fowler promised to do, although he has little help and is primarily interested in fish. Also talked to Fowler about having one of the girls

(Continued on Sept. 9)

Thursday, September 13, 1934

Went to work this morning at the USNM at 8:50. Found the specimens I had written about all laid out for me. Talked for a while with Miss Cochran, Myers, and Schmidt. Then worked all day steady on Crotalus types. Also made notes from the accession catalogs and copied some of the first pages thus settling questions with reference to old specimens. Got a pass which permitted me to work until 10 P.M. but went back to the hotel for supper at 8:55 tired out. 17 specimens counted in full today. Rained most all day.

Friday, September 14, 1934

Up early today planning the days work at the Museum . Laid out by numbers the points to investigate. Rained hard last night and ditto now. Got to the Museum at 8:45 taking sandwiches and fruit for lunch and supper; then worked until 9:15 and quit all tired out.

Made good headway with mitchellii and also looked over a lot of types of other kinds of snakes.

Discussed publication difficulties with Miss Cochran and found the same situation to exist everywhere. Both the American and National Museums are 4 or 5 years behind.

Showed Miss Cochran the rattler paper as completed to date.

Saturday, September 15, 1934

Began work at the National Museum this morning at 8:30. Spent quite a lot of time copying rattler entries out of the museum catalog for it is evident that if the specimens have been traded or lost there are no corresponding cards in the species file.

Then called on Dr. Styneger and talked with him for about an hour. He was very cordial. He discussed the early days of the museum and the relations with Cope. Talked with Dr. A. K. Fisher about the Death Valley expedition.

Started on cerastes.

Went to lunch today particularly to get mail of which none had arrived to date.

Worked all afternoon on cerastes and a few others and quit at 9:50

Eleanor called up at 10:35; will come to lunch tomorrow.

Sunday, September 16, 1934

Went to work at the museum this morning at 8:10; raining as usual.

First cleared up rarwiis items as to catalog cards etc. Then went to work on the types of goldmani and ravus which took until 10:30. Then worked on molossus and basiliscus until 1:05 when I had to quit to meet Eleanor and Rod for lunch. After lunch we went to the Zoo which we had some difficulty in locating. Went through the reptile house hurriedly; couldn't take much time as train time was imminent. It is well arranged but not as large as I had expected. They had a few interesting foreign snakes. Not much in the way of rattlers - only atrox and adamanteus. 1 Shopworn King Cobra. There was a large crowd present. Didn't try to see Mann; no time.

Caught the 4:10 for Chicago. Raining again - many autos stalled by floods along the way.

Thursday, September 20, 1934

See previous page
-------------------------------------------------------------
(Sept. 23th Continued)

It weighs 13 lbs, but is not so very long; probably does not exceed 5ft. He holds a pose when desired. While he rattles when handled, he does not offer to bite. She ties ribbons and hats on him. To me the most interesting specimens were her home raised atrox. These are California or Arizona stock - probably a mixture of the two; they have the usual creamy color (There was by contrast one very dark atrox from Texas, about the darkest I have ever seen). Of the first atrox brood there were 9 or 10 and 8 or 9 survive today. They were born on the 17th of June, 1932. Of these 4 have complete strings 3-15s and 1-14 (a female) and one is 15+1c. The rest have lost rattles. These are the finest complete strings I have ever seen.

There was a second brood born to the same parents; of these only 1 remains. They were born July 9, 1933. This one has 8c rattles.

For mites she uses soap and water, with good success, although not perfect.

(Continued on following page)

Page Edit History:
  • erintmas 04/19/2013 05:44 PM
  • erintmas 04/12/2013 05:05 PM
  • erintmas 04/12/2013 05:04 PM

Friday, September 21, 1934

At the office all day; went to a movie with Williams in the evening.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(Sept 23d continued from Sept 20)

The snakes are put in sacks and then the sacks are put in soapy water over night. She is much troubled with other diseases.

Her experiments lead her to believe that oreganus venom is much more neurotoxic than cerberus; however as she described them then were too few to be conclusive. She finds oreganus venom very powerful.

She seems to handle all the venomous snakes. I saw her handle puff-adders, Australian coral snakes, Australian black snakes, and tiger snakes. With King Cobras she uses more care but states that she has force fed, alone both King Cobras and Mambas. The King Cobras (one 14 ft. long) look in every way more dangerous than the mambas. The cobras would be far too powerful to handle by force. The mambas are much lighter and slimmer.

Australian black snakes bite each

(Continued on next page)

Saturday, September 22, 1934

At the office all day; went to "No More Ladies" with Williams in the evening.
-------------------------------------------------------------
(Continued from previous page)

other, seemingly without effect.

Saw a very beautiful Central American coral snake; also a small B. atrox.

She has a number of Galapagos iguanas - one sea iguana doing well on apples, bananas etc. Australian pythons are plentiful. There are a number of boas and 3 regal pythons; one 22 ft.

There are many interesting Australian lizards including skinks of various kinds, water dragons (5 young) and 2 frilled lizards. The water dragons hang around in a tree. There is some Spanish material. A beautiful green sceloporus. She tried small lizards in the large center cage but the large lizards ate them.

There is a large Yuma king snake raised from an egg from a specimen she got from Cook. It is very dark; the bands are hardly visible.

She hatches eggs by putting them in moistened leafmold, then covers with bark. Then warms with a light (with reflector)

(Continued on Sept 24)

Sunday, September 23, 1934

Worked in the morning.

Went out to the Brookfield Zoo in the L at about 2 PM, arriving at about 3, and stayed in the Zoo until 6:30, returning to the hotel at 8. Found the reptile house tremendously crowded so that it is very difficult to see anything on Sundays or holidays. Went to see Mrs. Wiley who shortly came into her office. We talked snakes and their care for an hour or more and then went out and looked at reptiles. First looked at those to which access is had from the rear of the cages; then after the people had gone out we looked over the others particularly those in the aluminum cages.

Mrs. Wiley has much of the material which she brought down from Minneapolis, some of which she has had for many years. A two headed turtle is doing well; it has grown to be a large animal. The rattlers are not exceptional; she has a good pink tigris from near Tucson, a number a good horridus, a S.D. Co. mitch and 2 rubers sent by Cook. One very large atrox from Texas is doing well; this she had for a long time

(Continued under Sept 20)

Monday, September 24, 1934

Dinner with Laura, Alice Miller and Shorty; then took Shorty to the train.

about 10" above. Moisten from time to time.

A green-headed snake from Central America was another handsome snake.

She has an alligator weighing over 200 lbs, raised from the egg.

Thursday, September 27, 1934

Enroute from Chicago; worked in the morning.

Arrived at San Bernardino at 1:10 and drove to San Diego, arriving at 5. Not in front seat so can't count. In our car Cummins, Williams, Arley and I; in Pecks, Lane, Bull, and Kuhn. Ray Keenan had the baggage in a light truck. Stopped for a few moments at Escondido sub.

Page Edit History:
  • erintmas 03/13/2013 11:23 PM

Friday, September 28, 1934

Very busy catching up.

From Earl Sanders received the following localities and notes:

Scutulatus 15 mi NE of Mesa, Ariz; (NW of Red Mountain or Red Rock).

Leptotyphlops humilis cahuilae 12 mi. E and 3 Mi N of Mesa. Caught in a black widow spider's web; was struggling when removed. Tail had been looped back and was held by the strands of the web.

Diadophis regalis arizonae. Fish Creek Canyon (SW of Roosevelt Dam)

Cook called this morning to see about future plans; told him no chance to talk until Sunday.

Recd today for examination a package of skins from Arrington and of snakes from E. H. Taylor.

The new window seat card filing case was at hand when I returned yesterday.

Page Edit History:
  • erintmas 04/12/2013 10:42 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:30 PM

Saturday, September 29, 1934

Worked all morning and most of the afternoon; then went up to the Zoo and Nat. Hist. for the first time since my return. Talked of trip with Mrs. Benchley, Perkins, and Gander. Secured specimens and package from Knowlton.

Saw a brood of horridus lately born at the zoo and still in good condition but have not shed yet.

Another timber rattler had 1 born prematurely and defective 9/11 another ditto 9/12. The mother died 9/17 with 3 well formed embryos all dead in the left oviduct; 1 egg and 1 deformed embryo in the right; therefore the total was 7.

Perkins told me of his trip 9/7. A high wind blowing; temperature about 88 degrees F.

1 Large sidewinder caught on 8 mi. E of Narrows
1 Large Leafnose caught on 1/2 mi W. of Co. Line
1 med Leafnose caught on 4 mi E of Narrows.

Tuesday, October 23, 1934

This morning at 7 P.M. started for Los Angeles, arriving at 10 AM. A clear warm day. Nothing seen. 54 miles in the county.

Returned in the afternoon - dark in the county.

Talked for an hour or so with Artran and Perkins. They gave me a fine lot of preserved rattlers which had died in their collection.

Artran told me of digging out 2 badgers in Arizona which had partly eaten a rattler he had tracked to their den. He found half the body and also remains in the extreta.

Cook and Hoard worked today.
